# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: polynomial-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] For linear-algebraic analysis of data, "fitting" usually means trying to find the curve that minimizes the vertical (*y*-axis) displacement of a point from the curve (e.g., ordinary least squares).
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] However, for graphical and image applications, geometric fitting seeks to provide the best visual fit; which usually means trying to minimize the orthogonal distance to the curve (e.g., total least squares), or to otherwise include both axes of displacement of a point from the curve.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Geometric fits are not popular because they usually require non-linear and/or iterative calculations, although they have the advantage of a more aesthetic and geometrically accurate result.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Most commonly, one fits a function of the form *y*=*f*(*x*).
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] A line will connect any two points, so a first degree polynomial equation is an exact fit through any two points with distinct x coordinates.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] This will exactly fit a simple curve to three points.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] A more general statement would be to say it will exactly fit four **constraints**.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Each constraint can be a point, angle, or curvature (which is the reciprocal of the radius of an osculating circle).
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Angle and curvature constraints are most often added to the ends of a curve, and in such cases are called **end conditions**.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Identical end conditions are frequently used to ensure a smooth transition between polynomial curves contained within a single spline.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Higher-order constraints, such as "the change in the rate of curvature", could also be added.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] This, for example, would be useful in highway cloverleaf design to understand the rate of change of the forces applied to a car (see jerk), as it follows the cloverleaf, and to set reasonable speed limits, accordingly.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] The first degree polynomial equation could also be an exact fit for a single point and an angle while the third degree polynomial equation could also be an exact fit for two points, an angle constraint, and a curvature constraint.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Many other combinations of constraints are possible for these and for higher order polynomial equations.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] If there are more than *n* + 1 constraints (*n* being the degree of the polynomial), the polynomial curve can still be run through those constraints.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] An exact fit to all constraints is not certain (but might happen, for example, in the case of a first degree polynomial exactly fitting three collinear points).
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] In general, however, some method is then needed to evaluate each approximation.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] The least squares method is one way to compare the deviations.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] The degree of the polynomial curve being higher than needed for an exact fit is undesirable for all the reasons listed previously for high order polynomials, but also leads to a case where there are an infinite number of solutions.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] For example, a first degree polynomial (a line) constrained by only a single point, instead of the usual two, would give an infinite number of solutions.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] This brings up the problem of how to compare and choose just one solution, which can be a problem for both software and humans.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Because of this, it is usually best to choose as low a degree as possible for an exact match on all constraints, and perhaps an even lower degree, if an approximate fit is acceptable.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Other types of curves, such as trigonometric functions (such as sine and cosine), may also be used, in certain cases.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] In spectroscopy, data may be fitted with Gaussian, Lorentzian, Voigt and related functions.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] In biology, ecology, demography, epidemiology, and many other disciplines, the growth of a population, the spread of infectious disease, etc. can be fitted using the logistic function.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] In agriculture the inverted logistic sigmoid function (S-curve) is used to describe the relation between crop yield and growth factors.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] The blue figure was made by a sigmoid regression of data measured in farm lands.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] It can be seen that initially, i.e. at low soil salinity, the crop yield reduces slowly at increasing soil salinity, while thereafter the decrease progresses faster.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] If a function of the form $y=f(x)$ cannot be postulated, one can still try to fit a plane curve.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Other types of curves, such as conic sections (circular, elliptical, parabolic, and hyperbolic arcs) or trigonometric functions (such as sine and cosine), may also be used, in certain cases.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] For example, trajectories of objects under the influence of gravity follow a parabolic path, when air resistance is ignored.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Hence, matching trajectory data points to a parabolic curve would make sense.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Tides follow sinusoidal patterns, hence tidal data points should be matched to a sine wave, or the sum of two sine waves of different periods, if the effects of the Moon and Sun are both considered.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] For a parametric curve, it is effective to fit each of its coordinates as a separate function of arc length; assuming that data points can be ordered, the chord distance may be used.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Coope approaches the problem of trying to find the best visual fit of circle to a set of 2D data points.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] The method elegantly transforms the ordinarily non-linear problem into a linear problem that can be solved without using iterative numerical methods, and is hence much faster than previous techniques.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] for points with Cartesian coordinates (x,y) on the border.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] For a data set of scattered points (xi,yi) and a fixed ellipse the right hand sides of this equation are no longer zero.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] One approach of fitting the points to an ellipse is to find the six parameters A to F such that the sum of the (squares of) the residual right hand sides is minimized.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] This leads to a linear least-squares fitting problem which is basically solved by finding eigenvectors of an associated 6 x 6 matrix which contains sums of mixed powers of (xi,yi).
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] The above technique is extended to general ellipses by adding a non-linear step, resulting in a method that is fast, yet finds visually pleasing ellipses of arbitrary orientation and displacement.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] The geometric fit minimizes the sum of the squared orthogonal distances of the data points to the border of the ellipse.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] A similar method that approximates these orthogonal distances is based on the Sampson metric.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Note that while this discussion was in terms of 2D curves, much of this logic also extends to 3D surfaces, each patch of which is defined by a net of curves in two parametric directions, typically called **u** and **v**.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] A surface may be composed of one or more surface patches in each direction.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] Many statistical packages such as R and numerical software such as the gnuplot, GNU Scientific Library, Igor Pro, MLAB, Maple, MATLAB, TK Solver 6.0, Scilab, Mathematica, GNU Octave, and SciPy include commands for doing curve fitting in a variety of scenarios.
[src:polynomial-regression/curve-fitting] There are also programs specifically written to do curve fitting; they can be found in the lists of statistical and numerical-analysis programs as well as in Category:Regression and curve fitting software.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] In mathematics, an **orthogonal polynomial sequence** is a family of polynomials such that any two different polynomials in the sequence are orthogonal to each other under some inner product.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The most widely used orthogonal polynomials are the classical orthogonal polynomials, consisting of the Hermite polynomials, the Laguerre polynomials and the Jacobi polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The Gegenbauer polynomials form the most important class of Jacobi polynomials; they include the Chebyshev polynomials and the Legendre polynomials as special cases.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] These are frequently given by the Rodrigues' formula.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The field of orthogonal polynomials developed in the late 19th century from a study of continued fractions by P.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Some of the mathematicians who have worked on orthogonal polynomials include Gábor Szegő, Sergei Bernstein, Naum Akhiezer, Arthur Erdélyi, Yakov Geronimus, Wolfgang Hahn, Theodore Seio Chihara, Mourad Ismail, Waleed Al-Salam, Richard Askey, and Rehuel Lobatto.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Given any non-decreasing function *α* on the real numbers, we can define the Lebesgue–Stieltjes integral $\int f(x)\,d\alpha (x)$ of a function *f*.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] This operation is a positive semidefinite inner product on the vector space of all polynomials, and is positive definite if the function α has an infinite number of points of growth.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] It induces a notion of orthogonality in the usual way, namely that two polynomials are orthogonal if their inner product is zero.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] In other words, the sequence is obtained from the sequence of monomials 1, *x*, *x*2, … by the Gram–Schmidt process with respect to this inner product.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Usually the sequence is required to be orthonormal, namely, $\langle P_{n},P_{n}\rangle =1,$ however, other normalisations are sometimes used.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Sometimes we have $d\alpha (x)=W(x)\,dx$ where $W:[x_{1},x_{2}]\to \mathbb {R}$ is a non-negative function with support on some interval [*x*1, *x*2] in the real line (where *x*1 = −∞ and *x*2 = ∞ are allowed).
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Such a *W* is called a **weight function**.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The most commonly used orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal for a measure with support in a real interval.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Discrete orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal with respect to some discrete measure.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Sometimes the measure has finite support, in which case the family of orthogonal polynomials is finite, rather than an infinite sequence.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The Racah polynomials are examples of discrete orthogonal polynomials, and include as special cases the Hahn polynomials and dual Hahn polynomials, which in turn include as special cases the Meixner polynomials, Krawtchouk polynomials, and Charlier polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Meixner classified all the orthogonal Sheffer sequences: there are only Hermite, Laguerre, Charlier, Meixner, and Meixner–Pollaczek.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] In some sense Krawtchouk should be on this list too, but they are a finite sequence.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] These six families correspond to the NEF-QVFs and are martingale polynomials for certain Lévy processes.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Sieved orthogonal polynomials, such as the sieved ultraspherical polynomials, sieved Jacobi polynomials, and sieved Pollaczek polynomials, have modified recurrence relations.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] One can also consider orthogonal polynomials for some curve in the complex plane.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The most important case (other than real intervals) is when the curve is the unit circle, giving orthogonal polynomials on the unit circle, such as the Rogers–Szegő polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] There are some families of orthogonal polynomials that are orthogonal on plane regions such as triangles or disks.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] They can sometimes be written in terms of Jacobi polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] For example, Zernike polynomials are orthogonal on the unit disk.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The advantage of orthogonality between different orders of Hermite polynomials is applied to Generalized frequency division multiplexing (GFDM) structure.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] More than one symbol can be carried in each grid of time-frequency lattice.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials of one variable defined by a non-negative measure on the real line have the following properties.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] where the constants *c**n* are arbitrary (depend on the normalization of *P**n*).
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] This comes directly from applying the Gram–Schmidt process to the monomials, imposing each polynomial to be orthogonal with respect to the previous ones.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] For example, orthogonality with $P_{0}$ prescribes that $P_{1}$ must have the form $P_{1}(x)=c_{1}\left(x-{\frac {\langle P_{0},x\rangle P_{0}}{\langle P_{0},P_{0}\rangle }}\right)=c_{1}(x-m_{1}),$ which can be seen to be consistent with the previously given expression with the determinant.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The converse is also true; see Favard's theorem.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] These recurrence relations are key for deriving properties of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] If the measure d*α* is supported on an interval [*a*, *b*], all the zeros of *P**n* lie in [*a*, *b*].
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Moreover, the zeros have the following interlacing property: if *m* < *n*, there is a zero of *P**n* between any two zeros of *P**m*.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Foata, and others, combinatorial interpretations were found for all the classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The Macdonald polynomials are orthogonal polynomials in several variables, depending on the choice of an affine root system.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] They include many other families of multivariable orthogonal polynomials as special cases, including the Jack polynomials, the Hall–Littlewood polynomials, the Heckman–Opdam polynomials, and the Koornwinder polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] The Askey–Wilson polynomials are the special case of Macdonald polynomials for a certain non-reduced root system of rank 1.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Multiple orthogonal polynomials are polynomials in one variable that are orthogonal with respect to a finite family of measures.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] These are orthogonal polynomials with respect to a Sobolev inner product, i.e. an inner product with derivatives.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Including derivatives has big consequences for the polynomials, in general they no longer share some of the nice features of the classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials with matrices have either coefficients that are matrices or the indeterminate is a matrix.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Quantum polynomials or q-polynomials are the q-analogs of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials can be defined as a vector basis set $P_{0},P_{1},P_{2},\dots$ of a symmetric bilinear form B on polynomials.
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] In the basis of the orthogonal polynomials, the bilinear form diagonalizes as $B(P_{i},P_{j})=B(P_{i},P_{i})\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:polynomial-regression/orthogonal-polynomials] Similarly, given a nondegenerate skew-symmetric bilinear form on polynomials, we can find a pair of vector basis sets $P_{0},P_{1},P_{2},\dots$ and $Q_{0},Q_{1},Q_{2},\dots$ , such that the bilinear form skew-diagonalizes as $B(P_{i},Q_{j})=B(P_{i},Q_{i})\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] In statistical modeling (especially process modeling), polynomial functions and rational functions are sometimes used as an empirical technique for curve fitting.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] where *n* is a non-negative integer that defines the degree of the polynomial.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] A polynomial with a degree of 0 is simply a constant function; with a degree of 1 is a line; with a degree of 2 is a quadratic; with a degree of 3 is a cubic, and so on.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Historically, polynomial models are among the most frequently used empirical models for curve fitting.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] These models are popular for the following reasons.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Polynomial models have well known and understood properties.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Polynomial models have moderate flexibility of shapes.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Changes of location and scale in the raw data result in a polynomial model being mapped to a polynomial model.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] That is, polynomial models are not dependent on the underlying metric.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Polynomial models are computationally easy to use.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] However, polynomial models also have the following limitations.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Polynomial models have poor extrapolatory properties.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Polynomials may provide good fits within the range of data, but they will frequently deteriorate rapidly outside the range of the data.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Polynomial models have poor asymptotic properties.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] By their nature, polynomials have a finite response for finite *x* values and have an infinite response if and only if the *x* value is infinite.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Thus polynomials may not model asymptotic phenomena very well.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] While no procedure is immune to the bias-variance tradeoff, polynomial models exhibit a particularly poor tradeoff between shape and degree.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] In order to model data with a complicated structure, the degree of the model must be high, indicating that the associated number of parameters to be estimated will also be high.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] This can result in highly unstable models.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] When modeling via polynomial functions is inadequate due to any of the limitations above, the use of rational functions for modeling may give a better fit.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] A rational function is simply the ratio of two polynomial functions.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] with *n* denoting a non-negative integer that defines the degree of the numerator and *m* denoting a non-negative integer that defines the degree of the denominator.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] For fitting rational function models, the constant term in the denominator is usually set to 1.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational functions are typically identified by the degrees of the numerator and denominator.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] For example, a quadratic for the numerator and a cubic for the denominator is identified as a quadratic/cubic rational function.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] The rational function model is a generalization of the polynomial model: rational function models contain polynomial models as a subset (i.e., the case when the denominator is a constant).
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational function models are a closed family.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] As with polynomial models, this means that rational function models are not dependent on the underlying metric.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational function models can take on an extremely wide range of shapes, accommodating a much wider range of shapes than does the polynomial family.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational function models have better interpolatory properties than polynomial models.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational functions are typically smoother and less oscillatory than polynomial models.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational functions have excellent extrapolatory powers.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational functions can typically be tailored to model the function not only within the domain of the data, but also so as to be in agreement with theoretical/asymptotic behavior outside the domain of interest.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational function models have excellent asymptotic properties.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational functions can be either finite or infinite for finite values, or finite or infinite for infinite *x* values.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Thus, rational functions can easily be incorporated into a rational function model.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational function models can often be used to model complicated structure with a fairly low degree in both the numerator and denominator.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] This in turn means that fewer coefficients will be required compared to the polynomial model.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Rational function models are moderately easy to handle computationally.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Although they are nonlinear models, rational function models are particularly easy nonlinear models to fit.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] One common difficulty in fitting nonlinear models is finding adequate starting values.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] A major advantage of rational function models is the ability to compute starting values using a linear least squares fit.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] To do this, *p* points are chosen from the data set, with *p* denoting the number of parameters in the rational model.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] which is derived from the previous equation by clearing the denominator.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] contain the subset of points, not the full data set.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] The estimated coefficients from this linear fit are used as the starting values for fitting the nonlinear model to the full data set.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] This type of fit, with the response variable appearing on both sides of the function, should only be used to obtain starting values for the nonlinear fit.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] The statistical properties of fits like this are not well understood.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] The subset of points should be selected over the range of the data.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] It is not critical which points are selected, although obvious outliers should be avoided.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] Unconstrained rational function fitting can, at times, result in undesired vertical asymptotes due to roots in the denominator polynomial.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] The range of *x* values affected by the function "blowing up" may be quite narrow, but such asymptotes, when they occur, are a nuisance for local interpolation in the neighborhood of the asymptote point.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] These asymptotes are easy to detect by a simple plot of the fitted function over the range of the data.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-and-rational-function-modeling] These nuisance asymptotes occur occasionally and unpredictably, but practitioners argue that the gain in flexibility of shapes is well worth the chance that they may occur, and that such asymptotes should not discourage choosing rational function models for empirical modeling.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] In statistics, **polynomial regression** is a form of regression analysis in which the relationship between the independent variable *x* and the dependent variable *y* is modeled as a polynomial in *x*.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Polynomial regression fits a nonlinear relationship between the value of *x* and the corresponding conditional mean of *y*, denoted E(*y* |*x*).
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Although polynomial regression fits a nonlinear model to the data, as a statistical estimation problem it is linear, in the sense that the regression function E(*y* | *x*) is linear in the unknown parameters that are estimated from the data.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Thus, polynomial regression is a special case of multiple linear regression.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The explanatory (independent) variables resulting from the polynomial expansion of the "baseline" variables are known as higher-degree terms.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Such variables are also used in classification settings.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Polynomial regression models are usually fit using the method of least squares.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The least-squares method minimizes the variance of the unbiased estimators of the coefficients, under the conditions of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The least-squares method was published in 1805 by Legendre and in 1809 by Gauss.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The first design of an experiment for polynomial regression appeared in an 1815 paper of Gergonne.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] In the twentieth century, polynomial regression played an important role in the development of regression analysis, with a greater emphasis on issues of design and inference.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] More recently, the use of polynomial models has been complemented by other methods, with non-polynomial models having advantages for some classes of problems.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The goal of regression analysis is to model the expected value of a dependent variable *y* in terms of the value of an independent variable (or vector of independent variables) *x*.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] is used, where ε is an unobserved random error with mean zero conditioned on a scalar variable *x*.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] In this model, for each unit increase in the value of *x*, the conditional expectation of *y* increases by *β*1 units.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] In many settings, such a linear relationship may not hold.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] For example, if we are modeling the yield of a chemical synthesis in terms of the temperature at which the synthesis takes place, we may find that the yield improves by a different amount for each unit increase in temperature.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Or we may find that the yield decreases with increasing temperature (but only for a certain range of temperatures) and increases with increasing temperature in a different range of temperatures.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Conveniently, these models are all linear from the point of view of estimation, since the regression function is linear in terms of the unknown parameters *β*0, *β*1, ....
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Therefore, for least squares analysis, the computational and inferential problems of polynomial regression can be completely addressed using the techniques of multiple regression.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] This is done by treating *x*, *x*2, ... as being distinct independent variables in a multiple regression model.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] can be expressed in matrix form in terms of a design matrix $\mathbf {X}$ , a response vector ${\vec {y}}$ , a parameter vector ${\vec {\beta }}$ , and a vector ${\vec {\varepsilon }}$ of random errors.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The *i*-th row of $\mathbf {X}$ and ${\vec {y}}$ will contain the *x* and *y* value for the *i*-th data sample.
