[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] This is the unique least-squares solution.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The above matrix equations explain the behavior of polynomial regression well.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] However, to physically implement polynomial regression for a set of xy point pairs, more detail is useful.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The below matrix equations for polynomial coefficients are expanded from regression theory without derivation and easily implemented.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Although polynomial regression is technically a special case of multiple linear regression, the interpretation of a fitted polynomial regression model requires a somewhat different perspective.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] It is often difficult to interpret the individual coefficients in a polynomial regression fit, since the underlying monomials can be highly correlated.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] For example, *x* and *x*2 have correlation around 0.97 when x is uniformly distributed on the interval (0, 1).
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Although the correlation can be reduced by using orthogonal polynomials, it is generally more informative to consider the fitted regression function as a whole.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Point-wise or simultaneous confidence bands can then be used to provide a sense of the uncertainty in the estimate of the regression function.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Polynomial regression is one example of regression analysis using basis functions to model a functional relationship between two quantities.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] A drawback of polynomial bases is that the basis functions are "non-local", meaning that the fitted value of *y* at a given value *x* = *x*0 depends strongly on data values with *x* far from *x*0.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] In modern statistics, polynomial basis-functions are used along with new basis functions, such as splines, radial basis functions, and wavelets.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] These families of basis functions offer a more parsimonious fit for many types of data.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] The goal of polynomial regression is to model a non-linear relationship between the independent and dependent variables (technically, between the independent variable and the conditional mean of the dependent variable).
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] This is similar to the goal of nonparametric regression, which aims to capture non-linear regression relationships.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Therefore, non-parametric regression approaches such as smoothing can be useful alternatives to polynomial regression.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] Some of these methods make use of a localized form of classical polynomial regression.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] An advantage of traditional polynomial regression is that the inferential framework of multiple regression can be used (this also holds when using other families of basis functions such as splines).
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] A final alternative is to use kernelized models such as support vector regression with a polynomial kernel.
[src:polynomial-regression/polynomial-regression] If residuals have unequal variance, a weighted least squares estimator may be used to account for that.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] As λ goes to zero, the inverse Box–Cox transformation becomes: $y=e^{z},$ an exponential model.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Therefore, the original inverse Box-Cox transformation contains a trio of models: linear (*λ* = 1), power (*λ* ≠ 1, *λ* ≠ 0) and exponential (*λ* = 0).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] This implies that on estimating λ, using sample data, the final model is not determined in advance (prior to estimation) but rather as a result of estimating.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] In other words, data alone determine the final model.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Extensions to the inverse Box–Cox transformation were developed by Shore (2001a) and were denoted Inverse Normalizing Transformations (INTs).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] They had been applied to model monotone convex relationships in various engineering areas, mostly to model physical properties of chemical compounds (Shore *et al.*, 2001a, and references therein).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Once it had been realized that INT models may be perceived as special cases of a much broader general approach for modeling non-linear monotone convex relationships, the new Response Modeling Methodology had been initiated and developed (Shore, 2005a, 2011 and references therein).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] and *ε*1 represents uncertainty (measurement imprecision or otherwise) in the explanatory variables (included in the LP).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] This is in addition to uncertainty associated with the response (*ε*2).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] where *Z* is a standard normal variate, independent of both *Z*1 and *Z*2, *ε* is a zero-mean error and d is a parameter.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] where *μ* (or *m*) is an additional parameter.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] The parameter “c” cannot be “absorbed” into the parameters of the LP (η) since “c” and LP are estimated in two separate stages (as expounded below).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] As shown earlier, the inverse Box–Cox transformation depends on a single parameter, *λ*, which determines the final form of the model (whether linear, power or exponential).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] All three models thus constitute mere points on a continuous spectrum of monotonic convexity, spanned by λ.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] This property, where different known models become mere points on a continuous spectrum, spanned by the model's parameters, is denoted the Continuous Monotonic Convexity (CMC) property.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] The latter characterizes all RMM models, and it allows the basic “linear-power-exponential” cycle (underlying the inverse Box–Cox transformation) to be repeated ad infinitum, allowing for ever more convex models to be derived.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Examples for such models are an exponential-power model or an exponential-exponential-power model (see explicit models expounded further on).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Since the final form of the model is determined by the values of RMM parameters, this implies that the data, used to estimate the parameters, determine the final form of the estimated RMM model (as with the Box–Cox inverse transformation).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] The CMC property thus grant RMM models high flexibility in accommodating the data used to estimate the parameters.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] References given below display published results of comparisons between RMM models and existing models.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] These comparisons demonstrate the effectiveness of the CMC property.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] It is realized that this series of monotonic convex models, presented as they appear in a hierarchical order on the “Ladder of Monotonic Convex Functions” (Shore, 2011), is unlimited from above.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] However, all models are mere points on a continuous spectrum, spanned by RMM parameters.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Also note that numerous growth models, like the Gompertz function, are exact special cases of the RMM model.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] An analogous expression may be derived without assuming *cZ* ≪ *η*.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] This would result in a more accurate (however lengthy and cumbersome) expression.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Once *cZ* in the above expression is neglected, *Y* becomes a log-normal random variable (with parameters that depend on *η*).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] RMM models may be used to model *random* variation (as a general platform for distribution fitting) or to model *systematic* variation (analogously to generalized linear models, GLM).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] In the former case (no systematic variation, namely, *η* = constant), RMM Quantile function is fitted to known distributions.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] If the underlying distribution is unknown, the RMM quantile function is estimated using available sample data.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Modeling random variation with RMM is addressed and demonstrated in Shore (2011 and references therein).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] In the latter case (modeling systematic variation), RMM models are estimated assuming that variation in the linear predictor (generated via variation in the regressor-variables) contribute to the overall variation of the modeled response variable (*Y*).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] This case is addressed and demonstrated in Shore (2005a, 2012 and relevant references therein).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] First the median is estimated by minimizing the sum of absolute deviations (of fitted model from sample data points).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] In the second stage, the remaining two parameters (not estimated in the first stage, namely, {*c*,*d*}), are estimated.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Three estimation approaches are presented in Shore (2012): maximum likelihood, moment matching and nonlinear quantile regression.
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Shore (2003a) developed Inverse Normalizing Transformations (INTs) in the first years of the 21st century and has applied them to various engineering disciplines like statistical process control (Shore, 2000a, b, 2001a, b, 2002a) and chemical engineering (Shore *at al.*, 2002).
[src:polynomial-regression/response-modeling-methodology] Concurrently, RMM had been applied to various scientific and engineering disciplines and compared to current models and modeling approaches practiced therein.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] Segmented linear regression with two segments separated by a *breakpoint* can be useful to quantify an abrupt change of the response function (Yr) of a varying influential factor (**x**).
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The breakpoint can be interpreted as a *critical*, *safe*, or *threshold* value beyond or below which (un)desired effects occur.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The figures illustrate some of the results and regression types obtainable.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] A segmented regression analysis is based on the presence of a set of ( **y, x** ) data, in which **y** is the dependent variable and **x** the independent variable.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The data may show many types or trends, see the figures.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] In the determination of the most suitable trend, statistical tests must be performed to ensure that this trend is reliable (significant).
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] When no significant breakpoint can be detected, one must fall back on a regression without breakpoint.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] indicating that soil salinities < 4.93 dS/m are safe and soil salinities > 4.93 dS/m reduce the yield @ 0.129 t/ha per unit increase of soil salinity.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The figure also shows confidence intervals and uncertainty as elaborated hereunder.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] 3. significance of the difference of A1 and A2 applying Student's t-distribution using the SE of their difference.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] 4. significance of the difference of Y1 and Y2 applying Student's t-distribution using the SE of their difference.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] A more formal statistical approach to test for the existence of a breakpoint, is via the pseudo score test which does not require estimation of the segmented line.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] In addition, use is made of the correlation coefficient of all data (Ra), the coefficient of determination or coefficient of explanation, confidence intervals of the regression functions, and ANOVA analysis.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] where Yr is the expected (predicted) value of **y** according to the former regression equations and Ya is the average of all **y** values.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The Cd coefficient ranges between 0 (no explanation at all) to 1 (full explanation, perfect match).
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] In a pure, unsegmented, linear regression, the values of Cd and Ra2 are equal.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] In a segmented regression, Cd needs to be significantly larger than Ra2 to justify the segmentation.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The optimal value of the breakpoint may be found such that the Cd coefficient is maximum.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] Segmented regression is often used to detect over which range an explanatory variable (X) has no effect on the dependent variable (Y), while beyond the reach there is a clear response, be it positive or negative.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The reach of no effect may be found at the initial part of X domain or conversely at its last part.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The method to find the no-effect range is progressive partial regression over the range, extending the range with small steps until the regression coefficient gets significantly different from zero.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] In the next figure the break point is found at X=7.9 while for the same data (see blue figure above for mustard yield), the least squares method yields a break point only at X=4.9.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] The latter value is lower, but the fit of the data beyond the break point is better.
[src:polynomial-regression/segmented-regression] Hence, it will depend on the purpose of the analysis which method needs to be employed.
